url.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first history of public health surveillance in the United States to span more than a century of conflict and controversy. The practice of reporting the names of those with disease to health authorities inevitably poses questions about the interplay between the imperative to control threats to the public's health and legal and ethical concerns about privacy. Authors Amy L. Fairchild, Ronald Bayer, and James Colgrove situate the tension inherent in public health surveillance in a broad social and political context and show how the changing meaning and significance of privacy have marked the politics and practice of surveillance since the end of the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConfidential communications. 0aPrivacy, Right of. 0aPublic health surveillance. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh  a20th century american healthcare.  a20th century american history.  aactivism.  aaids.  abirth defects.  acancer.  aconflict.  acontroversy.  ademocratic policy.  adetection.  adiagnosis.  adisease.  aethical concerns.  agovernment and governing.  ahealth authorities.  ahistory.  aillness.  aimmunization registry.  alegal concerns.  amedical.  aoccupational disease.  aprivacy.  apublic health surveillance.  apublic health.  areporting.  aresistance.  asecrecy.  asurveillance.  asyphilis.  aunited states of america.1 aBayer, Ronald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aColgrove, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFox, Daniel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilbank, Samuel L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of e